Source: verify-and-hunt re-hunt + ground-truth calibration (2026-06-02, round 2).

### crates/plsql-bindgen/src/emit.rs:58 — verdict=keep, severity=high
**Impact:** A crafted BindingPlan JSON (or --package value) whose package_name contains a newline escapes the single-line `// Generated by ...` header comment in the emitted Rust, smuggling attacker-chosen top-level items (`fn`/`mod`/`pub fn`) into the generated module — at minimum producing uncompilable Rust (denial-of-build), at worst injecting code that compiles and links into the downstream consuming crate.
**Evidence:** emit.rs:53-60 — emit_wrappers interpolates package_name raw into the header comment, no escaping:
  let _ = writeln!(out, "// Generated by plsql-bindgen for {} ({} routines).\n", plan.package_name, plan.routines.len());
emit.rs:278-291 — invalid_identifier_reason gates package_id (via package_id_problem), routine name, and every parameter name, but NEVER package_name.
emit.rs:246-265 — package_id_problem rejects non-[A-Za-z0-9_$#] chars (incl. newlines) for package_id; no sibling check exists for package_name.
lib.rs:50 — `pub package_name: String` is a plain serde Deserialize field with no validation.
main.rs:212 — `serde_json::from_str(&json)` deserializes a fully untrusted BindingPlan; main.rs:225 allows `--package` override; main.rs:242 writes the generated Rust to a file.
rg confirms emit.rs:58 is the ONLY raw interpolation of package_name into generated source (line 858 is a test f
**Repro:** Built the CLI, then end-to-end through `plsql-bindgen --input <plan> --output <file>` (both exit 0):
VARIANT 1 (denial-of-build): package_name = "demo\n}\nfn injected_top_level_item() { let x = 1; }\nmod m { " produced:
  // Generated by plsql-bindgen for demo
  }
  fn injected_top_level_item() { let x = 1; }
  mod m {  (0 routines).
  -> `rustc --edition 2021 --crate-type lib` fails: "error: unexpected closing delimiter: `}`" — uncompilable Rust.
VARIANT 2 (compilable token-smuggling): package_name = "demo\npub fn injected() -> i32 { 42 }\n//" produced:
  // Generated by plsql-bindgen for demo
  pub fn injected() -> i32 { 42 }
  // (0 routines).
  -> `rustc --edition 2021 --crate-type lib` 
**Suggested fix:** Fold CR/LF (and ideally all control chars) in package_name to a space before writing the header at emit.rs:55-60, e.g. `let safe: String = plan.package_name.chars().map(|c| if c == '\n' || c == '\r' { ' ' } else { c }).collect();` then interpolate `safe`. For defense in depth and to honor the documented fail-closed contract symmetrically, extend invalid_identifier_reason (or a sibling check) to reject newlines/control characters in package_name, and add a regression test feeding `package_name = "demo\n}\nfn injected() {}"` through emit_wrappers asserting the pre-routine preamble is a single `//`-prefixed line with no top-level fn/mod token outside the header comment.

### crates/plsql-bindgen/src/emit.rs:55 — verdict=keep, severity=medium
**Impact:** A build-time input (a crafted BindingPlan JSON or --package value) with an embedded newline in package_name injects arbitrary live Rust (e.g. a `use std::process::Command;` and a function) into the generated .rs file, smuggling code past the emitter's documented fail-closed guarantee and into any downstream crate that compiles the output.
**Evidence:** emit.rs:55-60 (raw interpolation, no escaping):
    let _ = writeln!(
        out,
        "// Generated by plsql-bindgen for {} ({} routines).\n",
        plan.package_name,
        plan.routines.len()
    );

Untrusted path (main.rs:212-228): `let mut plan: BindingPlan = serde_json::from_str(&json)` then `if let Some(name) = parsed.package { plan.package_name = name; }` then `emit_wrappers(&plan)`. BindingPlan is plain `#[derive(... Deserialize)]` (lib.rs:46-57) with no validation. write_output (main.rs:336) writes bytes verbatim.

Stated contract the field violates — emit.rs:332-348: "The CLI deserializes an UNTRUSTED BindingPlan ... Every other attacker-shaped plan fails closed with compilable Rust." Gates exist for package_id (package_id_problem, emit.rs:246), routine/param names (rust_ident_problem/invalid_identifier_reason, emit.rs:156/278), and SQL block via {block:?} Debug-escap
**Repro:** Triggering input /tmp/plan_inject.json with package_name = "DEMO\nuse std::process::Command;\nfn __pwned() { let _ = Command::new(\"id\"); }\n// neutralize".

`cargo run -q -p plsql-bindgen -- --input /tmp/plan_inject.json` (exit 0, no stderr) emits:
    // Generated by plsql-bindgen for DEMO
    use std::process::Command;
    fn __pwned() { let _ = Command::new("id"); }
    // neutralize (0 routines).

Lines 2-3 are live Rust items, not comment text. `rustc --edition 2021 --crate-type lib` on the emitted file compiles cleanly (exit 0), proving the injected items are real source, not inert.
**Suggested fix:** Render package_name through a fail-closed gate consistent with the rest of emit.rs rather than interpolating it raw. Minimal: strip CR/LF (and ideally all control chars) into a sanitized copy before the writeln!, e.g. `let safe_name: String = plan.package_name.chars().map(|c| if c.is_control() { ' ' } else { c }).collect();` then interpolate `{safe_name}`. Contract-consistent variant: reject any package_name containing control/newline characters and emit a BINDING_* diagnostic comment instead, mirroring package_id_problem. Add a regression test feeding a newline-laden package_name and asserting the whole emitted output parses as a comment-only header (no stray `use`/`fn` item), pairing with the existing compile-invalid-ident guard.

## Acceptance criteria
- [ ] Root-cause fix in production code; regression test fails before / passes after.
- [ ] `cargo test -p <crate>` + `cargo clippy -p <crate> --all-targets -- -D warnings` green; fmt only oraclemcp-*.
- [ ] No regression on existing tests / adversarial corpus.

AUDIT FINDING (plsql-bindgen, not previously tracked). crates/plsql-bindgen/src/emit.rs:87-89 emits every routine wrapper as:
  pub fn <name>(executor: &mut impl OracleExecutor, <in/inout>) -> Result<<Ret>, ExecutionError> {
      // TODO(bindgen): wire to executor.call_routine
      unimplemented!("BG-004 ... see plan §12.7")
  }
So generated bindings compile but panic at runtime — the bindgen product surface is non-functional. OracleExecutor (executor.rs:60) only exposes execute(sql,binds)->u64 and query(sql,binds)->Vec<Row>; there is no call_routine. Scope: (1) decide the invocation path — either add OracleExecutor::call_routine or have emit compose an anonymous 'BEGIN <pkg>.<routine>(:1,:2,...); END;' (or 'SELECT <fn>(...) FROM dual') block executed via execute/query with BindValue marshalling for IN/OUT/INOUT + return; (2) replace the unimplemented!() emission in emit.rs with the real body; (3) round-trip tests: emitted source compiles and a StubExecutor-backed call returns the mapped Rust type for scalar/record/OUT/return shapes. Ref plan §12.7.

Audit finding from /library-updater pass.

Gap. sha2 is pinned in 3 crates (catalog, store, mcp) at the same "0.10" string. workspace.dependencies already manages miette/serde/serde_json/thiserror/tracing in the same way. Moving sha2 there gives us one place to bump on future updates (see PLSQL-DEPS-001), eliminates drift risk, and is a 4-line change.

Proposed:
- Cargo.toml [workspace.dependencies]: add sha2 = "0.10"
- crates/plsql-catalog/Cargo.toml: sha2 = { workspace = true }
- crates/plsql-store/Cargo.toml: sha2 = { workspace = true }
- crates/plsql-mcp/Cargo.toml: sha2 = { workspace = true }

Safe: no API change, lockfile already resolves to the same version. Verify by cargo build + cargo test of the three crates.

P3 because it's cosmetic; bundle with DEPS-001 (sha2 0.11 bump) so the bump only touches the workspace entry.

Cite. None — local-only hygiene.

Source: verify-and-hunt + strict ground-truth calibration workflow (2026-06-02).

### Site crates/oraclemcp-core/src/shutdown.rs:84 — DEFENSE-IN-DEPTH (latent/phase-gated), severity=medium
**Impact:** None today (no production caller). Latent: once the serve loop awaits this coordinator, a SIGTERM that races startup can be lost, hanging the serve loop forever so graceful drain (in-flight rollback, lease revocation, pool drain) never runs and the process needs SIGKILL.
**Evidence:** crates/oraclemcp-core/src/shutdown.rs:84-89 (verbatim):
  pub async fn wait_for_shutdown(&self) {
      if self.is_shutting_down() { return; }      // flag checked BEFORE registering
      self.inner.notify.notified().await;          // waiter registers only on first poll
  }
begin_shutdown (lines 70-75): swap(true) then notify_waiters() — idempotent, fires at most once, stores no permit for future waiters.
tokio version: Cargo.lock -> tokio 1.52.3 (notify_waiters() stores no permit; Notified::enable() available).
Callers: `rg wait_for_shutdown crates/` -> only the def (84), a docstring (68), and two test sites (131,137). `rg ShutdownCoordinator|begin_shutdown|wait_for_shutdown` outside shutdown.rs -> only the lib.rs:42 re-export; the telemetry health.rs:45/116 begin_shutdown is a different method on HealthState. No serve-loop consumer exists.
Repro (faithful replica vs same tokio 1.52.3
**Repro/trigger:** Deterministic trigger (proven): (1) waiter evaluates is_shutting_down() == false; (2) before notified() is polled, another task calls begin_shutdown() -> swap(true)+notify_waiters() with no registered waiter and no permit stored; (3) waiter then polls notified(), registers fresh, and parks forever (begin_shutdown never fires again). A 500ms timeout around the replica's notified() expired, confirming the permanent hang. The claim's fix (let n = notify.notified(); pin!(n); n.as_mut().enable(); if is_shutting_down() {return;} n.await;) returned immediately in the same harness, closing the window. Impact-capped to defense-in-depth because grep proves no live code path reaches wait_for_shutdown —
**Suggested fix:** Register the Notify waiter before the flag check using the standard tokio idiom, then re-check:

    pub async fn wait_for_shutdown(&self) {
        let notified = self.inner.notify.notified();
        tokio::pin!(notified);
        notified.as_mut().enable(); // registers the waiter immediately (tokio >= 1.52)
        if self.is_shutting_down() {
            return;
        }
        notified.await;
    }

Add a regression test that calls begin_shutdown() before the waiter polls (reverse the existing 20ms-sleep ordering at shutdown.rs:133) and asserts wait_for_shutdown() returns promptly.

## Acceptance criteria
- [ ] Root cause fixed in production code (not just the symptom).
- [ ] A regression test reproduces the defect before the fix (fails) and passes after.
- [ ] `cargo test -p <crate>` + `cargo clippy -p <crate> --all-targets -- -D warnings` green; `cargo fmt` (oraclemcp-* only).
- [ ] No behavior regression on existing tests / adversarial corpus.

crates/plsql-mcp/src/audit.rs:167-170.

Current docstring:
  /// SQL that appends one audit row to the configured audit table.
  /// Returns None when no sink is configured. The bead skeleton uses a
  /// simple positional insert; the table schema is documented in
  /// docs/integrations/live-db/audit-table.md (follow-up).

Two flaws:

(1) 'The bead skeleton uses a simple positional insert' is self-effacing language in shipped code. The function is real, validated, and battle-tested (with_audit_table strictly validates the identifier against is_simple_sql_name and rejects anything that could escape the INSERT shape — see audit.rs:114-121 + 184-227). Calling its own implementation a 'bead skeleton' invites future maintainers to think this is placeholder code that can be ripped out, and tells OSS readers the same.

(2) The docstring references docs/integrations/live-db/audit-table.md — that file does not exist. Verified via filesystem check; the docs/integrations/ tree has no audit-table.md. A '(follow-up)' annotation is fine in an internal bead, but shipping it in a public Rust docstring tells readers 'this is documented elsewhere' when the documentation is vapor.

Same crate (plsql-mcp) was the subject of three other 'docstring self-declares stub / bead skeleton' findings in earlier rounds (oracle-37bb, oracle-cgcc, oracle-a9ix — all closed by rewriting the self-effacing language). This one was missed. Fix is mechanical: rewrite the docstring to describe the actual contract (positional insert with bind-parameterised tool_name + agent_program + agent_model + session_id + systimestamp; identifier-validated table name) and either land the audit-table.md or drop the (follow-up) reference.
